Brain Tumour MRI Image Classification¶

About the problem¶

Developing a deep learning model to classify brain MRI images as either healthy or abnormal for effective diagnosis of neurological conditions

The main objective of the Project¶

The MRI brain tumour image classification is a process that plays a vital role in identifying and classifying dangerous diseases, either benign or malignant. Research has been conducted to diagnose brain tumours based on medical images. The deep learning model should be evaluated accurately to classify the brain tumour MRI images of four tumour types: glioma, meningioma, no tumour and pituitary tumour.  The deep learning models has the ability that automatically learn complex features, model non-linear relationships, handle variability and continuously improve performance, ultimately aiding in accurate tumour classification and support clinical decision-making. 

By accurately identifying tumours at an early stage, healthcare professionals can make timely treatment decisions and improve patient outcomes. The model will learn unique characteristics and imaging patterns associated with each tumour type, providing valuable insights into underlying pathology. 

Ultimately, the project aims to enhance the accuracy and efficiency of brain tumour diagnosis, contributing to improved patient care and outcomes.

Definition¶

To Detect and Classify Brain Tumor using, Convolutional Neural Network(CNN) and Transfer Learning (TL); as an asset of Deep Learning and to examine the tumor position(segmentation).

Scope:¶

To develop a deep learning model for accurately classifying brain MRI scans into four tumour types: glioma, meningioma, no tumour and pituitary tumour. The focus is on achieving accurate tumour classification, early detection and supporting clinical decision-making.

Constraints:¶

- Availability of a diverse and well-labelled MRI dataset
- Computational resources
- Ensuring the models generalizability to different scanners
- Patient populations and confidentiality
- Addressing ethical considerations regarding data privacy
- Addressing interpretability challenges of the model’s decisions
- Deploying the model into clinical workflows

About the Dataset¶

Context¶

Brain Tumors are complex. There are a lot of abnormalities in the sizes and location of the brain tumor(s). This makes it really difficult for complete understanding of the nature of the tumor. Also, a professional Neurosurgeon is required for MRI analysis. Often times in developing countries the lack of skillful doctors and lack of knowledge about tumors makes it really challenging and time-consuming to generate reports from MRI’. So an automated system on Cloud can solve this problem.

Details¶

This dataset classifies the brain tumour MRI images into four tumour types:
- Glioma-826 images
- Meningioma-822 images
- No tumour-395 images 
- Pituitary tumour-827 images
    We have 2,870 images divided between Training, Testing and Validation.

1) Data Preprocessing

Model Architecture:¶

In [20]:
input_shape = (512, 512, 3)
model = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(8, (5,5), activation='relu', input_shape=input_shape ),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (5,5)),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(8, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (3,3)),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(8, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size = (2,2)),
    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation='softmax')
])
  • The model architecture is defined using the Sequential API of Keras.
  • It consists of several convolutional layers with max pooling, followed by flatten and dense layers.
  • Dropout layers are added to prevent overfitting.
  • The output layer has 4 units with softmax activation for multi-class classification (four tumor types).

Calculation for the above table¶

  • Conv2D layer:
    • Input Shape: (512, 512, 3) (assuming 512x512 RGB images)
    • Number of filters: 8
    • Filter size: 5x5
    • Total trainable parameters:
      • Weights: (5 5 3 * 8) + 8 = 608
      • Biases: 8
      • Total: 608
  • MaxPooling2D layer:
    • Pool size: 5x5
    • No trainable parameters.

  • Conv2D layer:

    • Number of filters: 8
    • Filter size: 3x3
    • Total trainable parameters: -Weights: (3 3 8 * 8) + 8 = 584 -Biases: 8 -Total: 584

  • MaxPooling2D layer:

    • Pool size: 3x3
    • No trainable parameters.

  • Conv2D layer:

    • Number of filters: 8
    • Filter size: 3x3
    • Total trainable parameters:
      • Weights: (3 3 8 * 8) + 8 = 584
      • Biases: 8
      • Total: 584

  • MaxPooling2D layer:

    • Pool size: 2x2
    • No trainable parameters.

  • Flatten layer:

    • No trainable parameters.

  • Dense layer:

    • Number of neurons: 128
    • Total trainable parameters:
      • Weights: (1800 * 128) + 128 = 230,528
      • Biases: 128
      • Total: 230,528

  • Dropout layer:

    • Rate: 0.2
    • No trainable parameters.

  • Dense layer:

    • Number of neurons: 64
    • Total trainable parameters:
      • Weights: (128 * 64) + 64 = 8,256
      • Biases: 64
      • Total: 8,256

  • Dropout layer:

    • Rate: 0.2
    • No trainable parameters.

  • Dense layer:

    • Number of neurons: 32
    • Total trainable parameters:
      • Weights: (64 * 32) + 32 = 2,080
      • Biases: 32
      • Total: 2,080

  • Dropout layer:

    • Rate: 0.2
    • No trainable parameters.

  • Dense layer (Output layer):

    • Number of neurons: 4 (corresponding to the 4 tumor types)
    • Total trainable parameters:
      • Weights: (32 * 4) + 4 = 132
      • Biases: 4
      • Total: 132

  • Total trainable parameters = (previous_layer_neurons * current_layer_neurons) + current_layer_neurons

  • Total trainable parameters = 616 + 592 + 592 + 230,656 + 8,320 + 2,112 + 136

  • Total trainable parameters = 242,772

A function plot_history is defined to plot the training and validation loss and accuracy over epochs.¶

In [26]:
def plot_history(history):
    hist = history.history
    hist['epoch'] = history.epoch
    epoch = np.array(hist['epoch'])
    loss=np.array(hist['loss'])
    val_loss=np.array(hist['val_loss'])
    accuracy = np.array(hist['accuracy'])
    val_accuracy = np.array(hist['val_accuracy'])
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))

    plt.subplot(2, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(accuracy, label = "Training accuracy")
    plt.plot(val_accuracy, label="Validation accuracy")
    plt.legend()
    plt.title("Training vs validation accuracy")


    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(loss, label = "Training loss")
    plt.plot(val_loss, label="Validation loss")
    plt.legend()
    plt.title("Training vs validation loss")
    
    plt.show()
